    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "| Metric    | Score      | Interpretation                                                     |\n",
        "| --------- | ---------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------ |\n",
        "| Accuracy  | **86.04%** | Overall, the model correctly classified 86% of the instances.      |\n",
        "| Precision | **79.01%** | Of all students predicted as placed, 79% were actually placed.     |\n",
        "| Recall    | **73.41%** | The model identified 73% of the students who were actually placed. |\n",
        "| F1-Score  | **76.11%** | Indicates a good balance between precision and recall.             |\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "### Confusion Matrix\n",
        "\n",
        "| **Actual \\ Predicted** | **Not Placed (0)** | **Placed (1)** |\n",
        "|:----------------------:|-------------------:|---------------:|\n",
        "| **Not Placed (0)**      | **6398** (True Negative) | **592** (False Positive) |\n",
        "| **Placed (1)**          | **807** (False Negative) | **2228** (True Positive) |\n",
        "### Confusion Matrix Summary\n",
        "\n",
        "| Metric | Value |\n",
        "|---------|------:|\n",
        "| True Positives (TP) | 2228 |\n",
        "| True Negatives (TN) | 6398 |\n",
        "| False Positives (FP) | 592 |\n",
        "| False Negatives (FN) | 807 |\n",
        "\n",
        "The model makes more false negatives (807) than false positives (592). In other words, it misses some students who actually got placed.\n",
        "\n",
        "Class 0 (Not Placed)\n",
        "Precision: 0.89\n",
        "Recall:    0.92\n",
        "F1-score:  0.90\n",
        "\n",
        "Class 1 (Placed)\n",
        "Precision: 0.79\n",
        "Recall:    0.73\n",
        "F1-score:  0.76\n",
        "\n",
        "This indicates the model predicts the Not Placed class more accurately than the Placed class. This is expected because your dataset appears to be somewhat imbalanced (6990 vs. 3035 samples)."
      ],
